Introduction
The primary elements of articial intelligence (AI) used to
make diodes and transistors, silicon (Si) and germanium
(Ge) doped with boron (B) and phosphorus (P) or gallium
(Ga) and arsenic (As) have an asymmetry due to boron.
Silicon and germanium are in group 14 like carbon (C) and
as such have 4 valence electrons. Thus to have positive
type silicon and germanium, they need doping agents from
group 13 (three valence electrons) like boron and gallium,
and to have negative type silicon and germanium they need
doping agents from group 15 like phosphorus and arsenic.
But where gallium and arsenic are in the same period as
germanium, boron is in a different period than silicon
(period 2) while phosphorus is not (group 3). Thus
aluminum (Al) is in borons place. This results in an
interesting equation.
The differential across germanium crossed with silicon plus
the differential across silicon crossed with germanium
normalized by the product between silicon and germanium
is equal to the boron divided by the average between the
germanium and the silicon. The equation has nearly 100%
accuracy:

Periodic Table of the AI Elements
I have a theory (my book Generalized Equation of Physical
Parameters) that suggests I nd a numerical scheme for the
elements of the periodic table that can allow me to manipulate
them mathematically. It seems to me this can best be done with
tensors. The theory, which results in equations for molar mass,
density, and atomic radii of articial intelligence (AI) elements
that are characterized by Stokes theorem (The relationship
between a surface integral to a line integral) can all be written in
a generalized equation that shows these parameters to all be
different manifestations of the same thing. The equations are
what I call dynamic, because they result from what I call an
asymmetry in the section of the periodic table of elements that
are the AI elements. This asymmetry is due to boron, because it
appears not where aluminum is, which would give that section of
the table symmetry. However by using aluminum as what I call a
dummy AI element, boron is predicted. We can see this
asymmetry if we look at the section of the table:
Here is my approach to a tensor formulation of what I call the
periodic table of the core AI elements.We take the standard
numbering of the elements in the periodic table

Then, we renumber it so that the rst indices in each number is
the row it is in, and the second is the valence number of the
element:

Semiconductor materials such as silicon (Si) have intrinsic
electron carriers, free electron that can carry a current, however
doped with elements such as phosphorus which have extra
electrons to donate to the silicon, we create negative or n-type
silicon. Doped with decient atoms, such as boron, holes are
created that can carry a current, or accept electrons making
positive, or p-type silicon. Joining n-type with p-type silicon
makes diodes, electric components that carry current in one
direction. With these we can make logic gates to create
programmable computers. The doping requires at minimum
and at a certain point ( ) becomes
degenerate. The higher the concentration of doping agents the
higher the conductivity of the silicon. We know that for silicon
in thermal equilibrium . That is, donors equal
acceptors equal intrinsic carriers. Since high level or
degenerate doping is often used for best conductivity, we
consider concentration for both donor and acceptor
concentrations, that is the same concentrations for n-type and p-
type silicon. The density of silicon is . Its molar mass
